The art of steel drums making started in 1945 in Trinidad where the activities of
World War Il had brought about an acute surplus of expendable 55 gallon oil drums.
The end of the drum is made concave about 3 or 4 inches toward the center with a
sledge hammer. After hammering, marking the notes with a chisel, the tones or notes
of the scale are hammered into each of the marked off spaces. The tuning process is
next and done by softening the metal through hammering each note. Your drum is
now ready to de played enner oy musical notes or by ear
